WEBVTT

00:01.820 --> 00:12.959
The boys were all in uniform, even the physically 
unfit boys wore a uniform with a NM on the collar,

00:01.820 --> 00:12.959
meaning non-military. There were no women on the 
campus other than secretaries, and even some of

00:14.782 --> 00:25.279
the department heads had male secretaries at that 
time. Before we start talking about Texas A&M,

00:25.934 --> 00:36.104
could I ask you a question about your decision to go 
into veterinarian sciences? Was it just because

00:37.185 --> 00:44.832
you grew up with these cattle, and was it because 
you had a neighbor who was a veterinarian, or were

00:37.185 --> 00:44.832
there other reasons? Well, that was the primary 
reason. Who knows why a kid wants to be a college

00:46.174 --> 00:53.461
clown, a circus clown, or a railway engineer or 
whatnot? Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm. The biggest thrill I

00:55.246 --> 01:02.816
ever got was when we went out and old Sal was trying 
to have pigs and the veterinarian's hand was too

00:55.246 --> 01:02.816
big. And I went in and pulled the pigs out and I got 
two dollars. I got it for that. He charged five and

01:11.467 --> 01:16.594
he gave me two because I could help him. And then he 
showed me how to clean out a horse's hoof and things

01:18.036 --> 01:23.363
like that. And all three years I worked in the 
foundry, I still had the back of my mind that I was

01:24.608 --> 01:31.197
going to be a veterinarian someday. Of course, 
they'd give me hands and arms.

01:38.027 --> 01:43.755
Were there, when you were working in the foundry, 
were there any other professions that you ever

01:38.027 --> 01:43.755
considered? No. No, in fact, when I went to Kansas 
State, they offered me a year's

01:54.865 --> 02:00.974
what do you call it, credit in engineering because 
of my foundry experience. I'd taken

02:03.137 --> 02:16.136
correspondence course while I worked in the 
foundry, metalurgy and so forth, but I always

02:03.137 --> 02:16.136
wanted to be a veterinarian. Okay, okay. Now can 
you explain your exactly what your functions or

02:22.118 --> 02:27.685
duties were when you came to Texas A&M? I helped Dr. 
Smith. Oh, you were his assistant. Yeah. I don't

02:33.752 --> 02:42.603
know whether you know it or not, but at that time 
there were three distinct entities on the A&M

02:33.752 --> 02:42.603
campus. There was the Texas Agriculture 
Experiment Station, there was the Texas

02:42.623 --> 02:50.252
Agriculture Extension Service, And there was a 
teaching college. And each one had its own

02:54.293 --> 02:56.796
separate head. And each one went to the 
legislature for its appropriation. So in other

03:04.547 --> 03:14.000
words, for example, we had a Department of 
Veterinary, of Dairy Science. We had an

03:15.442 --> 03:18.146
Experimentation Dairy Science. And we had an 
Extension Service Dairyman. They were not

03:21.164 --> 03:29.855
related to each other at all, administratively. 
Of course informally, there was a lot of give and

03:29.875 --> 03:32.158
take. Right,

03:32.759 --> 03:39.387
right. But

03:39.407 --> 03:50.361
we worked in the Veterinary Science Department of 
the Texas Ag God's Experimentation We worked on

03:52.163 --> 04:14.145
various diseases, including anthrax,

03:52.163 --> 04:14.145
brucellosis,

03:52.163 --> 04:14.145
mineral deficiencies, and parasitism.

04:14.165 --> 04:21.512
And Dr. Smith was primarily interested in 
pathology and mineral deficiencies. And he

04:22.808 --> 04:28.757
didn't care much for parasites.

04:31.261 --> 04:35.828
He gave that to me as my baby.

04:35.848 --> 04:50.571
And I became intensely interested in it and worked 
out a master's degree in biology because at that

04:35.848 --> 04:50.571
time there were no master's degrees in the School 
of Veterinary Medicine. It was a school. It wasn't

04:51.608 --> 04:52.389
a college. It was a school.

04:58.816 --> 05:13.692
And

04:58.816 --> 05:13.692
in 1937, they established a Department of 
Veterinary Parastrology in the School of

04:58.816 --> 05:13.692
Veterinary Medicine. A Dr. H.L. Van We

