Then the war came along

13:08.619 --> 13:20.937
and we went up on what you call the speed-up 
program. We took in a class every four months.

13:26.946 --> 13:28.007
Instead of one every year? Yeah. Well, why was 
that? Well, there weren't but about six or eight

13:30.993 --> 13:34.918
students in the class.

13:37.942 --> 13:42.108
So some years, we had graduations three times a 
year. In other words, the class of 45, some

13:44.231 --> 13:51.661
graduated in February and some along in April or 
May and some in September.

13:54.424 --> 13:58.570
And the entire veterinary faculty was reduced to 
about 12 people. From what was it before then,

13:59.630 --> 14:02.533
before the war? Oh, about 15 or 20, I imagine. 
Pardon

14:04.775 --> 14:22.272
me. I'll tell you how many there are now. Pardon me, 
I have to go to the bathroom. Fine.

15:28.021 --> 15:48.747
The name of the pathologist was Wharton, 
W-H-A-R-T-O-N.

15:28.021 --> 15:48.747
Now getting back to the war, did the war, did the 
war, was the federal government interested in

15:28.021 --> 15:48.747
increasing the number of veterinarians? Is that 
why you tripled the program? No. We were just

15:53.092 --> 15:57.758
trying to get enough credit hours on the books to 
get our paper from the state. In other words, we

15:58.818 --> 16:01.200
just had six boys in the class.

16:07.505 --> 16:09.487
Well, how did you, how did you, uh... I don't really 
know the reason for it. I was just a, I was an old man

16:11.509 --> 16:17.093
on a toilet bowl then. But I do know that we took, you 
can probably find someplace else, quiet. Yeah,

16:22.158 --> 16:23.779
okay, fine. But, fact remains, we took in the class 
every, every four months. Okay. In other, in any

16:30.442 --> 16:37.750
other ways did the war affect the vet school or your 
position? Well no, except that of course we had

16:38.951 --> 16:53.407
trouble getting supplies and we had instructors 
leaving because they were in the reserve or draft.

16:54.148 --> 16:57.732
For example, Dr. Armstead, Dr. Spangler, a whole 
bunch of them.

17:00.850 --> 17:01.972
went in as officers. That's why we're down to about 
12, or at the most, 14.

17:14.052 --> 17:22.947
Now getting back to the aim of the vet program, what 
did you think back in the late 1930s were the strong

17:14.052 --> 17:22.947
and weak points? Well. 1930s see I didn't come here 
in 36. Well that's yeah the late 1930s. And I was in

17:31.849 --> 17:47.907
Experiment Station until 1943 so

17:31.849 --> 17:47.907
I really didn't have too much to do with it except 
that of course Experiment Station would try to

17:31.849 --> 17:47.907
find out why things happened. Sure. And try to 
elaborate or devise a message of bringing disease

17:57.567 --> 18:09.443
under control, the

17:57.567 --> 18:09.443
good of veterinary medicine, I said, was 
primarily interested in turning out

17:57.567 --> 18:09.443
practitioners. In fact, Dr. Marks used to say, get 
the boys out with the animals. You can look at them

18:15.972 --> 18:17.995
flies on a cloudy day. And he took a rather dim view 
of laboratory procedures as such.

18:29.461 --> 18:32.985
but I don't really know. Actually the school 
didn't begin to really boom until after the war

18:33.025 --> 18:42.176
when the GIs came back. Now when you started 
teaching in 1943,

